\Editor{}
\begin{response}{
Actual scalability due to the required stored memory.
}
While the memory that the robot stores is important to the algorithm, scalability, with respect to the stored memory, is not. 
Specifically, each robot needs to only store their own trajectory information (often this is stored as discrete samples in time). 
The effective result of the past history is encoded into the Fourier spatial statistics $c_k$ that is then transmitted amongst each amongst robot that is locally connected.
Therefore, as the number of robots increases, the amount of data each robot has to store about itself remains constant. 

In order to clarify the scalability of the algorithm in the text, we added a few sentences that explain both the role of the memory and how this is only necessary for the individual robot to maintain.
\end{response}

